Interview Questions

Q1. What is the Stack class in Java?
-->Stack is a legacy class in the Java Collections Framework that extends the Vector class. It represents a LIFO (Last In, First Out) data structure, where the last element added is the first one to be removed.
      
      Since Stack extends Vector, it is synchronized (thread-safe) and allows duplicate and null elements.
      
      Example:
      
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
      
              stack.push(10);
              stack.push(20);
              stack.push(30);
      
              System.out.println(stack);
          }
      }
      
      Output
      
      [10, 20, 30]





Q2. How is Stack implemented internally?
-->Stack is implemented by extending the Vector class.

Internally:

It uses a dynamic array (Object[]) inherited from Vector.
Elements are added and removed only from the top of the stack.
Since it extends Vector, all methods are synchronized.

Example:

      Top
       ↓
      30
      20
      10

After pop():

      Top
       ↓
      20
      10




Q3. What are the methods of the Stack class (push(), pop(), peek(), etc.)?
-->
| Method             | Description                                              |
| ------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| `push(E item)`     | Adds an element to the top of the stack.                 |
| `pop()`            | Removes and returns the top element.                     |
| `peek()`           | Returns the top element without removing it.             |
| `empty()`          | Checks whether the stack is empty.                       |
| `search(Object o)` | Returns the 1-based position of an element from the top. |

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Stack<String> stack = new Stack<>();

        stack.push("Java");
        stack.push("Python");
        stack.push("C");

        System.out.println(stack.peek());
        System.out.println(stack.pop());
        System.out.println(stack.empty());
        System.out.println(stack.search("Java"));
    }
}

Output :
    C
    C
    false
    2




Q4. How many constructors are present in Stack?
-->Stack has one constructor.
      
      Default Constructor
      Stack<String> stack = new Stack<>();
      
      It creates an empty stack.
      
      Since Stack extends Vector, it inherits the dynamic resizing behavior of Vector.


